\begin_layout Standard
As chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP) has become a common laboratory technique
, combined with microarray techniques (ChIP on chip) and next generation
 sequencing (ChIP-Seq), our understanding of how histone modifications affect
 chromatin biology on a genome-wide scale has advanced dramatically.
 Profiling chromatin types using multiple datasets covering a large number
 of histone modifications is sufficient to predict the identity and function
 of regions in the genome with a high degree of accuracy, revealing previously
 unknown enhancers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Heintzman2007,Ernst2010,Hon2009"

\end_inset

.
 Ernst 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 used the genome-wide profiles of nine histone modifications in nine different
 cell types to define fifteen chromatin states, including promoters, enhancers,
 insulators and transcribed regions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ernst2011"

\end_inset

.
 They integrated data from genome-wide association studies (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "GWAS"
description "Genome-wide association study"

\end_inset

GWAS) and found numerous enhancer elements that coincide with disease associated
 mutations.
 Such genome-wide approaches can reveal differences between cell types and
 are powerful tools in understanding how the genome is interpreted in health
 and disease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Histone variants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to histone tail modifications, chromatin can be modified by
 the incorporation of histone variants.
 Canonical core histone genes are found in clustered repeat arrays within
 the genome, are transcribed during replication and are highly conserved
 between species.
 Histone variants are found as single genes spread through the genome and
 are subject to far greater diversity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Talbert2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CENP-A is a human variant of histone H3 which replaces the canonical histone
 in centromeric heterochromatin.
 It is a key factor in the establishment of the centromeres and kinetochores
 required for mitosis.
 The histone variant is incorporated with the help of a number of chaperone
 proteins, including HJURP, after replication of DNA has finished 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dunleavy2009,Foltz2009"

\end_inset

.
 CENP-A is essential for the formation of centromeres.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another frequent histone variant found in humans is H3.3, which differs from
 canonical H3 by just four amino acids 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Talbert2010"

\end_inset

.
 This histone variant is found within transcribed genes, promoters and regulator
y elements, and is thought to be laid down during transcriptional elongation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schwartz2005"

\end_inset

.
 Nucleosomes containing H3.3 appear to be less stable than canonical nucleosomes,
 with a high turnover 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schwartz2005"

\end_inset

.
 It is possible that this increased turnover of the nucleosomal components
 helps to keep the chromatin open and accessible to the transcriptional
 machinery 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Talbert2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other core histone proteins also have variants, such as H2A.Z, a histone
 variant located on either side of the nucleosome free regions
\emph on
 
\emph default
found at the transcriptional start sites of active genes as well as insulator
 regions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zlatanova2008"

\end_inset

.
 H2A.Z is able to promote the recruitment of RNA polymerase II to certain
 regions, such as the yeast 
\emph on
GAL1-10
\emph default
 genes,
\emph on
 
\emph default
by mediating C-terminal interactions with the transcriptional machinery
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Adam2001"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Higher order chromatin structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the key functions of histones are to package DNA into a compact form.
 The phosphate backbone of DNA carries a strong negative charge, negated
 by positively charged residues within the histone core particle.
 In its least compact configuration, chromatin forms a 10
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

nm fibre known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

beads on a string
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 At the other extreme chromatin forms mitotic chromosomes, condensing DNA
 10- to 20,000 fold 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Woodcock2010"

\end_inset

.
 Despite a great deal of research on forms of chromatin that exist between
 these two structures, definitive packing structures have not been forthcoming,
 primarily due to problems resolving individual chromatin strands within
 the nucleus by microscopy.
 Some evidence shows that a 30
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

nm fibre may exist, though the packing of nucleosomes in this structure
 is still a topic of debate (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Tremethick2007a"

\end_inset

).
 A recent paper by Fussner 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 suggests that all chromatin within 
\emph on
in-vivo
\emph default
 mouse nuclei is present as 10
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

nm fibres and that the 30
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

nm is not a common form of chromatin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fussner2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent investigations of genomic organisation using genome-wide association
 techniques have investigated the higher order packing of interphase chromatin
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lieberman-Aiden2009,Kalhor2011"

\end_inset

.
 Modelling approaches using this association data suggests that chromatin
 behaves like a fractal globule; unentangled chromatin packed upon itself
 in series of ever increasing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

globules
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Such a structure satisfies the need for chromatin to pack and unpack for
 mitosis without forming knots and is highly space efficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lieberman-Aiden2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Two-dimensional organisation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the inception of cytogenetics, it has been known that not all chromosomes
 are the same.
 The development of chromosome banding techniques in the 1970s allowed detailed
 human karyotypes to be determined, complete with differential staining
 of regions within each chromosome 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Caspersson1970"

\end_inset

.
 Banding assays can show regions of heterochromatin and euchromatin, highlightin
g the variation in characteristics across regions of the genome 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Trask2002"

\end_inset

.
 In prokaryotes, genes are often found in cistrons and can be coexpressed
 in single polycistronic mRNAs.
 This type of linear organisation is not present in most higher eukaryotes,
 with the notable exception of the nematode worm 
\emph on
Caenorhabditis elegans
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Blumenthal2002"

\end_inset

, though gene clusters resulting from tandem duplication are frequently
 found throughout mammalian genomes.
 Some specific examples of two-dimensional clustering have been shown: testes-sp
ecific genes in 
\emph on
Drosophila melanogaster 
\emph default
have been found in clusters more frequently than would be expected by chance
\emph on
 
\emph default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Boutanaev2002"

\end_inset

 and genes sharing transcription factors can be found in clusters in the
 yeast 
\emph on
Saccharomyces
\emph default
 
\emph on
cerevisiae
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Janga2008"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sequencing of the human genome allowed detailed analysis of GC content,
 gene density and repetitive sequence content 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lander2001"

\end_inset

.
 Versteeg 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 integrated a multitude of 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "SAGE"
description "Serial analysis of gene expression"

\end_inset

 SAGE tag expression profiles from different cell types into the genomic
 map and built on earlier work defined regions of high transcriptional activity,
 called ridges 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Versteeg2003,Caron2001"

\end_inset

.
 They found ridges to be gene-dense, highly transcribed, have a high GC
 content and low LINE repeat density.
 These features are based purely on the underlying sequence content and
 so do not vary amongst cell types.
 The different ridges and anti-ridges were found to contain different classes
 of genes, with weakly expressed genes clustering within anti-ridges and
 clusters of highly expressed housekeeping genes found predominantly in
 ridges 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Versteeg2003"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a gross scale, chromosomes are formed by two arms denoted p and q, connected
 by a centromere and capped by telomeres.
 Centromeres and telomeres contain primarily repetitive sequence and are
 important for the structural maintenance of chromosomes.
 Chromosomes 13, 14, 15, 21, 22 and Y are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

acrocentric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: the p arms are so short that they are difficult to observe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whilst the two-dimensional organisation of the genome cannot completely
 explain the degree of complexity found within the transcriptome, these
 studies demonstrate that the order of sequence within the genome is not
 entirely random and can affect the transcriptional control of genes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chromosome Territories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As chromosomes decondense after metaphase they retain some degree of structure,
 forming 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

chromosome territories
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CT"
description "Chromosome territory"

\end_inset

CTs) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cremer2001"

\end_inset

.
 Circumstantial evidence for interphase organisation of chromosomes has
 existed for a long time, first suggested by Carl Rabl in 1885 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rabl1885"

\end_inset

.
 Oberservations by Stack 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 using microscopy with giemsa-band staining suggested that chromosomes retained
 some degree of organisation during interphase 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stack1977"

\end_inset

, and in 1982 Cremer 
\emph on
et al., 
\emph default
showed that interphase chromosomes occupy territories by studying the pattern
 of DNA damage in metaphase chromosomes after spot irradiation during interphase
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cremer1982"

\end_inset

.
 The subsequent development of chromosome paints, a method to visualise
 entire or part-chromosomes with fluorescence 
\emph on
in-situ
\emph default
 hybridisation (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "FISH"
description "Fluorescence in-situ hybridisation"

\end_inset

FISH), confirmed these findings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schardin1985a,Manuelidis1985,Bolzer2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

