\begin_layout Standard
As FISH techniques have developed, so too has the detail with which CT organisat
ion can be studied.
 Several groups have shown that chromosome territory position within the
 nucleus is not random and correlates with chromosome size 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sun2000,Cremer2001b,Bolzer2005"

\end_inset

, gene-density 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cremer2001b,Croft1999"

\end_inset

 and replication timing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ferreira1997,Visser1998"

\end_inset

 - those near the centre of the nucleus tend to be gene-rich, early replicating
 and small.
 CT positioning appears to be conserved through evolution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tanabe2002"

\end_inset

 and is cell type specific 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Parada2004b,Kuroda2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
CTs and transcription 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:CTs-and-transcription"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is known that for some but not all genes, positioning at the nuclear
 periphery correlates with reduced gene expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kosak2002,Dietzel2004,Zink2004a"

\end_inset

.
 To investigate whether nuclear positioning can cause changes in transcriptional
 activity or is simply a consequence, three groups published studies which
 artificially tethered genomic regions to the inner nuclear membrane using
\emph on
 lac
\emph default
 operators 
\emph on
(lacO)
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Finlan2008,Reddy2008,Kumaran2008"

\end_inset

.
 Finlan 
\emph on
et al.
 
\emph default
and Reddy 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 both observed a decrease in the transcriptional activity of the regions
 when tethered 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Finlan2008,Reddy2008"

\end_inset

, an effect that was ablated when cells were treated with trichostatin A
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "TSA"
description "Trichostatin A"

\end_inset

TSA) to inhibit class I and class II histone deacetylases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Finlan2008"

\end_inset

.
 It should be noted that this effect does not appear to apply to all loci
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kumaran2008"

\end_inset

.
 Whilst these studies suggest that it is nuclear positioning that leads
 to transcriptional effects, a study by Croft 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 showed that inhibition of transcription causes a reversible change in CT
 position 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Croft1999"

\end_inset

 and Bridger 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 showed a difference in CT positioning between proliferating and senescent
 human fibroblasts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bridger2000"

\end_inset

.
 Large scale rearrangements of CTs have also been observed during cell different
iation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stadler2004,Szczerbal2009"

\end_inset

, likely due to changes in transcriptional profiles and chromatin remodelling.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This evidence suggests that there is a dynamic interplay between CT positioning
 and transcription - gross transcriptional patterns may drive the position
 of chromosomes within the nucleus, and those positions may in turn affect
 the transcription of the genes they contain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chromosome territory dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The movement of chromatin loci within the nucleus is known to be largely
 due to local Brownian motion, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constrained diffusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and seems to be limited by attachment to a nuclear cytoskeleton, nucleoli
 and the inner nuclear membrane 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marshall1997,Chubb2002"

\end_inset

, though some studies have shown a mixture of local diffusion and larger,
 active movements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vazquez2001"

\end_inset

.
 Chuang 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 studied Chinese hamster ovary (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CHO"
description "Chinese hamster ovary cells"

\end_inset

CHO) cells after stimulation with a transcriptional activator and analysed
 the movement of a reporter locus from the nuclear periphery to the interior
 of the nucleus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chuang2006"

\end_inset

.
 They found that chromosome movements happened in rapid unidirectional bursts,
 suggesting an active mechanism.
 This was supported by a later study in human fibroblast cells by Mehta
 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 who demonstrated chromosome movement only 15 minutes after serum starvation,
 a process that was ablated by the inhibition of actin polymerisation or
 myosin activity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mehta2010"

\end_inset

.
 Such rapid movements on such a large scale come at a large energy cost
 to the cell and indicate the importance of chromosome positioning in nuclear
 function.
 
\end_layout

