name "sec:Transcription-factories"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fully understand the structure and function of the genome, we must see
 it in the context of the nuclear proteome.
 Proteinaceous subcompartments are found within the nucleus and aid the
 control of chromatin dynamics and efficient functioning of related processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One class of nuclear subcompartment which has come to light within the past
 thirty years is the
\emph on
 
\emph default
transcription factory, seen as foci of hyper-phosphorylated RNA polymerase
 II scattered throughout the nucleus.
 The vast majority of genic transcription appears to take place at transcription
 factories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1993,Osborne2004,Ragoczy2006,Eskiw2008a,Schoenfelder2010"

\end_inset

, challenging the classical model of transcription found in many text books
 (discussed below).
