 genome 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sanyal2012"

\end_inset

.
 To achieve the resolution required for the robust detection of promoter-element
 interactions, Sanyal 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 used 5C, a many-to-many technique that uses a panel of oligonucleotides
 with common adapters to anneal to 3C products and create a library capable
 of being sequenced.
 They sequenced libraries from three ENCODE cell lines: K562, HeLa-S3 and
 GM12878.
 Only a small proportion of the looping interactions uncovered were shared
 between the three cell types, with approximately 60% of interactions being
 unique to a single cell line.
 The majority of TSS looping interactions could be classified as interacting
 with enhancer elements, promoters or regions bound by the structural protein
 CTCF.
 Looping interactions with enhancer elements were significantly enriched
 for actively expressed TSS, demonstrating the importance of three-dimensional
 chromatin contacts in the regulation of gene expression.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What drives nuclear organisation? 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:What-drives-nuclear-organisation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As our understanding of the structure of the nucleus evolves, an increasing
 number of structural features and patterns are being uncovered.
 Teasing apart correlation and causation to find the driving forces behind
 nuclear organisation is not an easy task and remains a major challenge
 within the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transcription 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:drives-organisation-Transcription"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discovery of transcription factories has changed our view of nuclear
 organisation substantially.
 If genetic templates are mobile and transcription factories are fixed,
 then it maybe be possible to use the process of transcription as a tool
 to fold the genome into specific conformations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kimura 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 quantified the amount of stable RNA polymerase II in HeLa cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kimura1999"

\end_inset

 adding to the work by Jackson 
\emph on
et al.
 
\emph default
demonstrating the stability of nascent transcripts and polymerase in the
 nucleus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1981,Jackson1985"

\end_inset

.
 Mitchell and Fraser later demonstrated that RNA polymerase II transcription
 factories remain in the absence of transcription, though gene association
 with factories is ablated if transcription initiation is inhibited 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mitchell2008"

\end_inset

.
 These data, along with the observation that genes are recruited to pre-existing
 transcription factories upon activation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Osborne2004"

\end_inset

, support a model whereby transcription factories are attached to a relatively
 immobile nuclear substructure.
 This means that RNA polymerase II can act as a motor, dragging template
 chromatin through the nucleus as it is transcribed, powered by the removal
 of phosphate groups during RNA synthesis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cook1999"

\end_inset

.
 Yin 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 measured the force produced by a single 
\emph on
E.
 coli
\emph default
 RNA polymerase using an immobilised enzyme transcribing a template bound
 to a polystyrene bead held by optical tweezers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yin1995"

\end_inset

.
 RNA polymerase stalled when the force applied was greater than 14 piconewtons
 (pN), substantially more than kinesin or myosin, making RNA polymerase
 the most powerful biological motor known.
 Papantonis 
\emph on
et al.
 
\emph default
demonstrated the potential of RNA polymerase to pull chromatin transcripts
 through the nucleus 
\emph on
in vivo
\emph default
 by using 3C to measure the change in association between regions of DNA
 after activation of the 
\emph on
TNF
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 gene 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Papantonis2010"

\end_inset

.
 They found that as the gene was transcribed, downstream regions of chromatin
 progressively came into contact with other transcribing regions at the
 transcription factory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The role for transcription in the organisation of the genome is further
 supported by the pervasive nature of transcription.
 As much as 93% of genomic bases in the human genome are though to be transcribe
d in at least one cell type (described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Clark2011"

\end_inset

), including many enhancers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ling2005,Kim2010"

\end_inset

.
 In the recent ENCODE study of TSS interactions, Sanyal 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 found that enhancer elements looping to a TSS were significantly more likely
 to express enhancer RNAs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sanyal2012"

\end_inset

, supporting a model that the transcription of a chromatin template could
 be responsible for the formation of chromatin loops.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An attractive model for larger scale genome organisation revolves around
 the transcription of housekeeping and tissue-specific genes.
 Lercher 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 have shown that genes with high expression in multiple tissue types have
 a propensity to be present in clusters within the genome 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lercher2002"

\end_inset

 and the mouse alpha globin locus has been shown to assemble at a transcription
 factory already transcribing a cluster of housekeeping genes in erythroid
 cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhou2006"

\end_inset

.
 Gavrilov 
\emph on
et al.
 
\emph default
showed that these housekeeping genes were bound stably to the nuclear matrix
 and resistant to high salt extraction, whereas the alpha globin genes were
 less stable and could be eluted 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gavrilov2010"

\end_inset

.
 These studies may point to a model of the nucleus where persistently transcribe
d housekeeping genes are held in transcription factories, with tissue specific
 genes being recruited to these sites upon activation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mitchell2008,Gavrilov2010"

\end_inset

.
 Such a system could have far reaching consequences, with chromosome conformatio
n being determined by housekeeping gene hubs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
CTCF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CTCF (CCCTC-binding factor) is a highly conserved DNA-binding protein with
 eleven zinc finger domains which binds the consensus sequence CCCTC as
 well as a range of variant sequences using combinations of different zinc
 fingers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Filippova1996"

\end_inset

 (Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ctcf-structure"

\end_inset

, reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Ohlsson2001"

\end_inset


\emph on
)
\emph default
.
 The core sequence has extremely high sequence conservation between mouse,
 chicken and human and mice homozygous for the gene knockout exhibit early
 embryonic lethality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Splinter2006"

\end_inset

.
 The protein is expressed ubiquitously and misregulation by over-expression
 or RNAi knockdown have a wide range of effects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Torrano2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

