\begin_layout Standard
When CTCF was first isolated it was thought to be a transcriptional repressor
 for the 
\emph on
c-Myc 
\emph default
gene 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lobanenkov1990"

\end_inset

.
 Since then its proposed functions have included transcriptional activator
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vostrov1997"

\end_inset

, insulator and structural protein.
 Bell, West and Felsenfeld were the first to characterise the role of CTCF
 as an insulator in a study of the chicken beta-globin locus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bell1999"

\end_inset

.
 They showed that CTCF binds the HS4 region of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-globin LCR, a region previously shown to act as an insulator in a transgene
 enhancer-blocking assay 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chung1997"

\end_inset

.
 One of the best characterised examples of CTCF acting as an enhancer is
 at the imprinted 
\emph on
H19/Igf2
\emph default
 locus.
 Four CTCF binding sites were found in the imprinting control region (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "ICR"
description "Imprinting control region"

\end_inset

ICR) which exhibit methylation-sensitive binding 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bell2000,Hark2000,Szabo2000"

\end_inset

.
 On the unmethylated maternal allele, CTCF binds the ICR and the downstream
 enhancer element stimulates expression of the 
\emph on
H19
\emph default
 gene.
 On the methylated paternal allele, CTCF binding is abrogated and the enhancer
 contacts the distal 
\emph on
Igf2
\emph default
 gene instead, causing expression of 
\emph on
Igf2
\emph default
 and not 
\emph on
H19
\emph default
.
 This model is supported by 3C data showing parent-of-origin specific interactio
ns between the enhancer and the two genes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murrell2004,Kurukuti2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Genome wide studies of CTCF binding using ChIP-on-chip and ChIP-Seq have
 greatly developed our understanding of this complex protein.
 The model of CTCF acting as a global transcriptional activator or repressor
 has been largely abandoned; binding by CTCF is not able to predict transcriptio
nal activity or correlate with specific classes of genes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chen2008"

\end_inset

.
 In support of CTCF in the role of a global insulator, Xie 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 determined a large number of conserved CTCF binding sites using computational
 analysis and derived a dataset containing divergent pairs of genes with
 and without a CTCF separating them 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Xie2007"

\end_inset

.
 Divergent gene pairs facing away from each other frequently show correlated
 expression patterns 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Trinklein2004,Li2006b"

\end_inset

 - as expected, gene pairs not separated by a CTCF site showed a propensity
 to be coexpressed, yet those with a CTCF site had a close to background
 level chance of coexpression 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Xie2007"

\end_inset

.
 Not all CTCF binding sites appear to act as enhancer-blocking insulators
 however, as demonstrated by looping over CTCF sites in the human beta-globin
 locus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tolhuis2002"

\end_inset

.
 The recent 5C study by Sanyal 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 found that 79% of long range interactions skip one or more CTCF binding
 sites, prompting the authors to suggest that additional factors may be
 needed for the insulator function of CTCF 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sanyal2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The development of the ChIA-PET technique has allowed an in depth interrogation
 of chromatin interactions associated with specific proteins by incorporating
 a ChIP step with a 3C-derived assay 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fullwood2009a"

\end_inset

.
 Handoko 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 used ChIA-PET to investigate CTCF bound chromatin interactions in mouse
 embryonic stem (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "ES cell"
description "Embryonic stem cell"

\end_inset

ES) cells and suggested that CTCF acts in multiple roles with different
 sizes of loops 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Handoko2011"

\end_inset

.
 Correlative analysis using data describing surrounding histone modifications
 allowed the authors to determine five distinct classes of CTCF-derived
 loops: active domains enriched for H3K4me1, H3K4me2 and H3K36me3; repressive
 domains enriched for H3K9, H3K20 and H3K27 methylation; putative enhancer-promo
ter interactions; barrier insulator behaviour, separating active and inactive
 chromatin compartments; and finally, loops with no known correlation or
 function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Handoko2011"

\end_inset

.
 This study illustrates the complexity of CTCF binding within the genome
 and points to multiple roles for the protein involving chromatin organisation.
 This interaction has subsequently been shown to be dependent on protein-protein
 contacts between the SA2 subunit of cohesin and the C-terminal domain of
 CTCF 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Xiao2011"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cohesin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structural maintenance of chromosome (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "SMC"
description "Structural maintenance of chromosome proteins"

\end_inset

SMC) proteins, also known as cohesin, form complexes required for sister
 chromatid cohesion and chromosome segregation in mitosis.
 Originally characterised in 
\emph on
Drosophila melanogaster 
\emph default
due to mutants having a defect in sister chromatid separation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Michaelis1997"

\end_inset

, cohesin is a multi subunit complex consisting of two large coiled-coil
 domain proteins (Smc1, Smc3) connected by a smaller dimer of Scc1 and Scc3.
 Cohesin complexes are thought to function in mitosis by holding sister
 chromatids together through topological looping (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Hudson2009"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A number of studies suggested that cohesin may play a role in the interphase
 nucleus as well as in mitosis, being implicated in gene regulation, recombinati
on, repair and domain formation (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Hagstrom2003"

\end_inset

).
 In 2008 three studies showed that the genome-wide binding profiles of cohesin
 subunits in mammalian cells correlates highly with that of CTCF 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Parelho2008,Wendt2008,Rubio2008"

\end_inset

.
 Parelho 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 expressed a FLAG-tagged cohesin subunit of Rad21 in mouse lymphoid cell
 lines which was able to pull down the SMC1, SMC3 and SA1 cohesin subunits.
 They generated ChIP-chip libraries covering approximately 3% of the mouse
 genome and determined that cohesin binds DNAse hypersensitive regions enriched
 for a motif highly similar to the CTCF consensus binding sequence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Parelho2008"

\end_inset

.
 Wendt 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 followed a similar path, using the HeLa cell line to create ChIP-chip libraries
 covering approximately 1% of the human genome for both SMC3 and CTCF 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wendt2008"

\end_inset

.
 Rubio 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 studied the binding partners of CTCF by mass spectrometry and found that
 Scc3/SA1 was a key binding partner, leading them to create ChIP-chip libraries
 for CTCF and Scc3/SA1 in HBL100 cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rubio2008"

\end_inset

.
 All three studies came to the same conclusion - that the majority of CTCF
 and cohesin binding sites overlap in mammalian genomes, leading to a model
 where the sequence specific binding of CTCF is responsible for the targeting
 of the cohesin complex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In these investigations, cohesin has been implicated at many if not most
 of the loci described in the above sections.
 Stedman 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 and Wendt 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 both demonstrated that cohesin is enriched at the CTCF binding sites of
 the imprinted 
\emph on
H19/Igf2
\emph default
 locus in the same methylation- and parent of origin- sensitive manner and
 that this binding is ablated upon mutation of the CTCF sites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stedman2008,Wendt2008"

\end_inset

.
 Enrichment of cohesin at this locus is also disrupted in mutants lacking
 the C-terminal domain of CTCF responsible for binding cohesin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Xiao2011"

\end_inset

 and the presence of cohesin is required for the three-dimensional conformation
 of the locus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nativio2009"

\end_inset

.
 Cohesin has also been implicated in the control of the beta-globin locus
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wendt2008,Hou2010"

\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
Ifng
\emph default
 / T
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
H
\end_layout

\end_inset

2 LCR 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Parelho2008,Hadjur2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CTCF depletion does not affect the amount of cohesin bound to the genome,
 but rather the enrichment of cohesin at specific sites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Parelho2008,Wendt2008"

\end_inset

.
 Schmidt 
\emph on
et al.
 
\emph default
showed
\emph on
 
\emph default
a subset of cohesin bound regions independent of CTCF binding in MCF-7 cells
 which colocalise with ER-
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 binding 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schmidt2010"

\end_inset

.
 A similar association of cohesin and mediator / Nipb1 at promoters and
 enhancers in ES cells has been described 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kagey2010"

\end_inset

.
 These studies suggest an attractive hypothesis that multiple tissue-specific
 proteins may be able to target cohesin binding to specific sites to affect
