\begin_layout Subsection
Tethering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nucleus is a structured organelle which contains a number of architectural
 features such as nuclear pores, the inner nuclear membrane (nuclear lamina)
 and the nucleolus.
 Chromatin can bind to these regions in a specific nature leading to changes
 in nuclear organisation and gene expression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As microscopy studies have advanced our understanding of how the genomic
 positioning of genes can affect expression, it has became clear that associatio
n with the nuclear periphery generally correlates with gene silencing (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kosak2002,Dietzel2004,Zink2004a,Finlan2008,Reddy2008"

\end_inset

; discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:CTs-and-transcription"

\end_inset

).
 In 2008, Guelen 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 used the DamID technique with lamin-B1 tethered to DNA adenine methyltransferas
e (Dam) to identify regions of the genome associated with the nuclear lamina
 in human lung fibroblasts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Guelen2008"

\end_inset

.
 They found that the fraction of lamina-associated chromatin on each chromosome
 correlated with known CT positioning preferences in fibroblasts.
 Their key finding was that chromatin-lamina associations existed as distinct
 regions, termed lamina associated domains (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "LAD"
description "Lamina associated domain"

\end_inset

LADs).
 The domains range from 0.1 to 10 megabases in size and are enriched for
 chromatin marks associated with transcriptional repression: H3K27me3, H3K9me2,
 low H3K4me2, low RNA polymerase II, low gene expression and low gene density.
 LAD boundaries are enriched for CTCF binding and CpG island, suggesting
 a mechanism of association 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Guelen2008"

\end_inset

.
 Shimi 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 showed in the same year that Lamins A and B form separate meshes on the
 inner nuclear membrane and relatively static structures within the nuclear
 matrix, hinting at the existence of highly complex micro-environments based
 on the binding of chromatin to lamin networks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Shimi2008"

\end_inset

.
 A subsequent study investigating cells with a mutation in the 
\emph on
LMNA
\emph default
 lamin gene has shown that the position, compaction and transcriptional
 activity of some lamin-associated regions are affected 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mewborn2010"

\end_inset

, suggesting that the many diverse conditions caused by lamin mutations
 may arise due to changes in chromatin structure and so gene expression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although LADs are associated with low gene expression, not all chromatin
 at the nuclear membrane is silenced.
 Early electron micrographs showed regions of less dense chromatin at nuclear
 pores (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Capelson2009,Arib2011"

\end_inset

).
 This observation was recently validated with the observation of nuclear
 pore complexes (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "NPC"
description "Nuclear pore complex"

\end_inset

NPCs) contacting channels with heterochromatin using a new form of sub-diffracti
on limit light microscopy able to simultaneously image NPCs, lamins and
 chromatin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schermelleh2008"

\end_inset

.
 Nuclear pore proteins have been found to be associated with active regions
 of chromatin and are present both at NPC and within the nucleoplasm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vaquerizas2010,Kalverda2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Actin and myosin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presence of nuclear actin has been debated for many years; its initial
 detection often labelled as artefacts due to the inability of phalloidin
 to stain actin fibrils within the nucleus (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Hofmann2006"

\end_inset

).
 Despite this skepticism, nuclear actin research has had a resurgence in
 recent years with studies linking filamentous actin to processes such as
 transcription 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hofmann2004"

\end_inset

 and nuclear export 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hofmann2001"

\end_inset

.
 McDonald 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 used fluorescence recovery after photobleaching (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "FRAP"
description "Fluorescence recovery after photobleaching"

\end_inset

FRAP) microscopy to study nuclear actin in HeLa cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McDonald2006"

\end_inset

.
 Treatment with latrunculin which inhibits the polymerisation of actin lead
 to a loss of a slow moving population of actin, suggesting the existence
 of polymeric actin in the nucleus.
 Within the cytoplasm, force is generated through interaction between bundles
 of filamentous actin and polymerised myosin II.
 The nucleus does not contain any myosin II, though an isoform of myosin
 I incapable of forming filaments has been detected 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pestic-Dragovich2000"

\end_inset

.
 Two papers from the Belmont and Bridger groups recently demonstrated active
 reorganisation of chromosome territory positioning which was dependent
 on the action of actin and myosin 1 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chuang2006,Mehta2010"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our understanding of how nuclear actin and myosin are involved in nuclear
 organisation is still in its infancy, yet is rapidly gaining traction as
 techniques are developed which allow us to probe and manipulate their behaviour
 within the nucleus without disrupting cytoplasmic processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Replication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proliferating cells must replicate their genomes once per cell cycle and
 do so in only a few hours, despite their size.
 This is accomplished by simultaneously replicating many regions of the
 genome at shared sites called replication factories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1998b,Ma1998"

\end_inset

.
 The genome is replicated in an organised manner; active genes are linked
 to early replication and inactive genes tend to replicate late (reviewed
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Goren2003"

\end_inset

).
 Clusters of replication foci that share replication factories continue
 to associate through multiple cycles of cell division 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1998b"

\end_inset

.
 Many studies have shown correlation between behaviour in replication and
 genomic features or activity, though causative links are still lacking
 (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chakalova2005"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polycomb
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another nuclear subcompartment known to be involved in genomic organisation
 and looping is the polycomb body.
 The Polycomb protein complex (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "PcG"
description "Polycomb protein complex"

\end_inset

PcG) is involved in the directed silencing of regions at polycomb response
 elements (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "PRE"
description "Polycomb response element"

\end_inset

PREs), mediated by repressive histone modifications such as H3K27me3 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cao2002"

\end_inset

, and are important for the maintenance of silencing of the 
\emph on
Hox
\emph default
 genes (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Pirrotta1998"

\end_inset

).
 Long range interactions and chromatin looping has been implicated in repression
 by PcG proteins 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Tiwari2008,Tiwari2008a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The bigger picture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When seen as a whole, many of the models described above are not mutually
 exclusive.
 Many hold in common the presence of chromatin loops within the nucleus
 and describe domains of chromatin defined by epigenetic marks.
 It seems entirely plausible that the overall structure of the nucleus is
 determined by the combined result of many different processes directing
 specific interactions, driven by different processes and stabilised by
 different types of contact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chromosomal translocations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the major medical implications of genomic organisation is how it
 may relate to the formation of chromosomal translocations.
 Specific chromosomal rearrangements are frequently associated with certain
 cancer types, and can be highly predictive of patient prognosis.
 Furthermore, cancers involving different translocations can respond to
 treatments in different ways, paving the way for patient-specific treatment
 regimes (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Mitelman2007"

\end_inset

).
 Understanding the principles of chromosomal translocation formation is
 an important step in the development of novel treatments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Formation of chromosomal translocations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the development of chromosome banding microscopy, it has been known
 that the genetic material within cancerous cells is frequently disrupted.
 Chromosomal translocations involve the rearrangement of genetic material
 between non-homologous chromosomes through the formation and aberrant repair
 of at least two double strand breaks (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "DSB"
description "Double strand break"

\end_inset

DSBs) that are situated on different chromosomes.
 The resulting product can be a straight swap (balanced translocations)
 or can result in deletions or even gain of material after malsegregation
 in mitosis (unbalanced translocations).
 Chromosomal translocations can involve multiple DSBs on different chromosomes
 resulting in hugely complex karyotypes, especially in cells predisposed
 to translocations due to defects in repair.
\end_layout

