\begin_layout Subsubsection
DSB repair
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Double strand breaks can be caused by exogenous damage (ionising radiation,
 free radicals) and endogenous damage (physiological programmed DSBs).
 As many as 1 million DNA lesions are formed per cell per day 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "AlbertsLewisRaffRobertsWalter2007"

\end_inset

 and can be highly deleterious to the cell, causing loss of genetic material,
 translocations and ultimately cell death if left unrepaired.
 Mammalian cells have an array of different DSB repair pathways that depend
 on the cellular context and type of lesion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Longhese2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Homologous recombination (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "HR"
description "Homologous recombination"

\end_inset

HR, Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DSB-repair"

\end_inset

B) repairs double strand breaks by using long regions of homology on undamaged
 sister chromatids or homologous chromosomes.
 HR is primarily active during cell replication and rarely leads to serious
 chromosomal rearrangements or translocations, although â€˜crossing-overâ€™
 can sometimes occur, whereby two sections of homologous chromosomes switch
 to their partner chromosomes.
 This process is encouraged during meiosis with the formation of chiasmata,
 crossovers that are 10
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
4
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to 10
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
5
\end_layout

\end_inset

 times more frequent than in mitosis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lee2009"

\end_inset

.
 During meiosis homologous chromosomes are preferentially used for HR to
 promote crossovers, but sister chromatids are more commonly used in mitosis
 to minimise variation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schwacha1997,Haber2000"

\end_inset

.
 Non-allelic homologous recombination (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "NAHR"
description "Non-allelic homologous recombination"

\end_inset

NAHR) is a variation of HR characterised by the aberrant use of low-copy
 repeats during strand invasion.
 NAHR can result in duplications, inversions and translocations and is responsib
le for a number of spontaneous genetic disorders such as Potocki-Lupski
 syndrome 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Potocki2007"

\end_inset

 and cancers involving recurring breakpoints 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Darai-Ramqvist2008"

\end_inset

 (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Gu2008"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Single strand annealing (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "SSA"
description "Single strand annealing"

\end_inset

SSA, Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DSB-repair"

\end_inset

C) creates a short region of single stranded DNA at the site of the DSB
 which is used to search for regions of microhomology, usually repeat sequences
 in the same orientation.
 These regions anneal and any excess single stranded tails are removed to
 allow the nicks to be ligated.
 SSA is prone to introducing deletions into the genome, and can form chromosomal
 translocations if two sequences with similar repeat regions are nearby,
 and both suffer simultaneous DSBs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-homologous end joining (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "NHEJ"
description "Non-homologous end joining"

\end_inset

NHEJ, Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DSB-repair"

\end_inset

A) is a last resort for the cell, whereby any two adjacent DSBs are ligated,
 needing little or no sequence homology.
 This pathway is extremely prone to errors as it is capable of joining any
 two strands of DNA irrespective of their identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A number of serious conditions exist due to mutations in genes key in the
 DSB repair pathways described above.
 Ataxia telangiectasia is an autosomal-recessive neurodegenerative disease
 caused by mutations in the 
\emph on
ATM
\emph default
 gene which is involved in NHEJ and HR 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Beucher2009"

\end_inset

.
 Fanconi anaemia is a condition caused by mutations in one of a number of
 proteins involved in DSB recognition and repair which is associated with
 a high incidence of leukaemia and a number of congenital defects.
 Blooms syndrome is characterised by a excessive HR and genomic instability
 caused by mutations in the 
\emph on
BLM
\emph default
 gene.
 These, and other similar diseases, are indicative of the importance of
 DSB repair and the danger of genomic instability.
\end_layout

