\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Philadelphia chromosome
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This genetic abnormality, primarily associated with CML, was first the first
 consistent chromosomal abnormality found with any cancer.
 Identified in 1960 by Nowell and Hungerford 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nowell1960"

\end_inset

 they noticed the presence of an abnormal chromosome and called it the Philadelp
hia chromosome, or Ph chromosome, after the city in which it was discovered.
 The chromosome was initially thought to be the result of a deletion until
 chromosome banding enabled its identification as a product of a translocation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rowley1973"

\end_inset

.
 The breakpoints within chromosomes 9 (cytogenetic band q34) and 22 (band
 q22) were subsequently identified as being within the 
\emph on
c-ABL
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
BCR
\emph default
 genes, respectively.
 The 
\emph on
c-ABL 
\emph default
gene (also known as 
\emph on
ABL1) 
\emph default
was named as such because of its similarity to the Abelson murine leukaemia
 virus gene 
\emph on
v-ABL 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rowley2001"

\end_inset

.

\emph default
 Less is known about the 
\emph on
BCR
\emph default
 gene, so named because it was found at the Breakpoint Cluster Region of
 chromosome 22.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Occurance stats
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The
\emph on
 ABL1
\emph default
 gene encodes a tyrosine kinase which is ubiquitously expressed in mammalian
 cells.
 Involved in cell cycle regulation, it is thought to be involved in several
 cell signalling pathways 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Deininger2000"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
BCR
\emph default
 protein contains a serine-threonine kinase and has GTPase activity, but
 its function is not known 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Deininger2000"

\end_inset

.
 The t(9;22)(q34;q11) translocation creates a fusion protein lacking the
 SH2 domain of 
\emph on
ABL1
\emph default
 which normally regulates its activity.
 This results in constitutively active tyrosine-kinase activity which drives
 oncogenesis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Deininger2000"

\end_inset

.
 The mechanism of translocation formation is yet to be characterised, though
 ionising radiation is known to be a risk factor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tanaka1989,Corso1995"

\end_inset

.
 Identification and characterisation of the 
\emph on
BCR-ABL
\emph default
 translocation and its fusion protein led to the development of a number
 of kinase inhibitors such as the drug 
\emph on
imatinib
\emph default
 (also known as 
\emph on
gleevec
\emph default
), which achieve excellent success in the treatment of CML and a number
 of other cancers involving the t(9;22)(q34;q11) translocation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hehlmann2007"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mixed lineage leukaemia
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acute leukaemia is typically categorised as either Acute Lymphoblastic Leukaemia
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "ALL"
description "Acute Lymphoblastic Leukaemia"

\end_inset

ALL) or Acute Myeloid Leukaemia (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "AML"
description "Acute Myeloid Leukaemia"

\end_inset

AML) according to which lineage of blood cells are cancerous.
 ALL is defined by the uncontrolled proliferation of lymphoblasts, precursors
 to lymphocytes which differentiate into B cells, T cells and NK cells.
 ALL was estimated to account for approximately 12% of all leukaemia cases
 in the US in 2008 with around five and a half thousand cases occurring
 annually.
 It is the most common form of cancer in children aged under fourteen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jemal2009"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Better stats? UK?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AML is a cancer of the myeloid lineages of blood cells, responsible for
 approximately 30% of all cases of leukaemia in the US for 2008 with a higher
 mortality rate than ALL (66% and 27% mortality for AML and ALL, respectively)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jemal2009"

\end_inset

.
 The incidence of AML increases with age; the median age of AML diagnosis
 between 2002 and 2006 in the US was 67 years, and the median age of mortality
 was 72 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jemal2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The biology of leukaemia is not always as discrete as this classification
 however, some patients present with expansion of both lymphoid and myeloid
 lineages 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Matutes1997"

\end_inset

.
 Two genetic abnormalities sometimes found in these patients include the
 t(9;22)(q34;q11) Philadelphia chromosome and structural changes in 11q23
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Matutes1997"

\end_inset

.
 Chromosomal translocations within band q23 of chromosome 11 have been implicate
d in both AML and ALL, all involve the gene 
\emph on
MLL
\emph default
 (also known as 
\emph on
ALL-1
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Htrx
\emph default
, 
\emph on
HRX
\emph default
) identified by Ziemin-van der Poel 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 in 1991 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ziemin-vanderPoel1991"

\end_inset

.
 Translocations involving the 
\emph on
MLL
\emph default
 gene are found in over 70% of all infant leukaemias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Biondi2000"

\end_inset

 and approximately 10% of adult AML cases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krivtsov2007"

\end_inset

.
 The translocation correlates with poor patient prognosis and is of high
 clinical interest 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chen1993"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Leukaemia stem cells
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2002, Armstrong 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 showed that acute lymphoblastic leukaemias containing a translocation within
 the 
\emph on
MLL
\emph default
 gene have a unique expression profile that is different to ALL and AML,
 and suggests an origin within a less committed progenitor cell which can
 produce cells in both the myeloid and lymphoid cell lineages 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Armstrong2002"

\end_inset

.
 They suggest that these leukaemias are substantially different from AML
 and ALL and deserve a new, distinct, class of leukaemia called Mixed Lineage
 Leukaemia (MLL).
 Further cytogenetic studies have supported this theory; leukaemic cells
 in MLL have been found to express cell surface antigens normally present
 on both myeloid and lymphoid cells such as CD14 and CD19 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krivtsov2007"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The suggestion that MLL is initiated within a progenitor cell is in line
 with previous evidence showing that some cases of ALL and AML are initiated
 within undifferentiated haematopoietic stem cells (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "HSC"
description "Haematopoietic stem cell"

\end_inset

HSCs) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sutherland1996,Bonnet1997"

\end_inset

.
 HSCs are present within the CD34
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
+
\end_layout

\end_inset

 progenitor cell population, accounting for approximately 3% of normal human
 bone marrow and 0.3 to 0.5% of human cord blood mononuclear cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Libura2008"

\end_inset

.
 They are long lived and capable of self-renewal, differentiating into lineage
 restricted progenitors and eventually mature terminally differentiated
 white blood cells.
 HSCs are necessary for the long term maintenance of the haematopoietic
 system and are commonly used to repopulate bone marrow after myeloablative
 therapy, as well as in the treatment of a number of other disorders such
 as autoimmune, cardiac and vascular diseases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Burt2008"

\end_inset

.
 Cancer stem cells are thought to be present in both leukaemias and solid
 tumours 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hamburger1977"

\end_inset

 and HSCs are a probable founder population due to their ability to self-renew
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Reya2001"

\end_inset

.
 The concept of a small pool of cancer stem-cells driving the large heterogeneou
s pool of cancer cells has a number of implications for treatment - these
 are the cells that must be targeted for the efficient and long lasting
 cure of cancer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Reya2001"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The MLL protein
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MLL protein is a H3K4 methyltransferase involved in the positive regulation
 of global gene regulation, including the maintenance of expression of the
 
\emph on
Hox
\emph default
 genes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yu1995"

\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
MLL
\emph default
 is required for embryonic haematopoiesis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hess1997"

\end_inset

 and adult bone marrow maintenance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jude2007"

\end_inset

.
 MLL is a mammalian homologue of the 
\emph on
Drosophila melanogaster
\emph default
 trithorax complex and is thought to bind DNA via an AT-hook domain 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zeleznik-Le1994"

\end_inset

 and a zinc finger domain 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Birke2002"

\end_inset

.
 It is thought that the zinc finger domain targets MLL to unmethylated CpG
 island DNA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Birke2002"

\end_inset

 and ChIP studies have shown that MLL binds to a subset of transcribed genes
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Milne2005"

\end_inset

.
 MLL binds promoters and gene bodies, associating tightly with RNA polymerase
 II 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Milne2005"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All known MLL fusion proteins contain exons 8-13 of 
\emph on
MLL 
\emph default
and in-frame exons of a partner gene 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krivtsov2007"

\end_inset

.
 Fusion proteins always retain their AT-hook and zinc-finger CxxC motifs,
 which are essential for their transforming potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Slany1998"

\end_inset

.
 The H3K4 methyltransferase domain of MLL is often lost in fusion proteins
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krivtsov2007"

\end_inset

, despite this the fusion proteins can drive constitutive expression of
 
\emph on
HOXA9
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
MEIS1
\emph default
 which, if over-expressed together in the absence of a MLL fusion protein,
 give a similar phenotype 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zeisig2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

